buildkit directly handles configuration and patches, which are
inherently dependent on the Chromium version. Having this separated into
an environment variable poses two issues:
1. It breaks usage as a library (without hacking os.environ or setting
the variable beforehand)
2. It encourages manipulation, even though such a use-case is
nonsensical.

Thus, buildkit now behaves like it did before to reading version.ini at
startup.

Because there seems to be no reference to the logic for generating the
chromium-browser-official tar file, it's possible that it is being generated
by an internal script that manually injects the GN repository files.
Therefore, assume that the GN version used in the chromium-browser-official tar
files correspond to the latest commit in the master branch of the GN repository
at the time of the tar file's generation. We can get an approximation for the
generation time by using the last modification date of the tar file on
Google's file server.

buildkit: Ignore symlinks in domain substitution application

Certain platforms, such as Debian, symlink some files listed in the
domain substitution list to files in the system. We don't want to
substitute these files, since it will cause a permission error.

Any files that have domains in the Chromium source tree should already be
listed by their real paths in the domain substitution list, so any path
that has become a symlink must be due to some source tree modification.

Add missing includes to flag-fingerprinting-canvas-webgl-noise

This solution is a compromise/hack. The ideal solution would be to
extend third_party/skia with a public function that can do the data
shuffling, but that would require separating the Skia-dependent
constants from the algorithm, which is also interleaved with
dependencies on //base (which Skia isn't).

However, given that Skia seems to insert "Sk" or include "skia"
somewhere in all its names (file and variable names) means that it
should be fine to add those to the includes of
//third_party/blink/renderer/platform without much risk of
introducing a name conflict bug.

The Skia includes/private directory is chosen for inclusion since
SkColorData.h (and dependencies) only depend on includes within
that directory, so this would have the smallest impact in terms of
namespace pollution.

utils/downloads.py: Remove axel downloader

When downloading the official Chromium tar file, axel is no longer able
to parallelize the connections nor detect the filesize. It is likely
Google added a specific rule for axel since curl and Chromium work
normally. While it is possible to circumvent this rule, Google might
have imposed it to reduce spikes of heavy load on their servers. We
should respect this and just use curl instead, which only uses one
connection and has the ability to resume interrupted downloads.

Add write permission to read-only files so their domains can be subsituted

This was added because both `third_party/shaka-player/dist/package.json` and
`third_party/shaka-player/dist/shaka-player.ui.extens.js` are read-only when
extracted from the chromium source tarball. Currently, this change could
potentially be replaced by manual vetting and whitelisting of the
beforementioned files from the domain subsitution routine. Another alternative
to this approach would be to pass an argument to tar (or whatever other program
is used to perform the extraction) that specifies that the extracted files are
to be writable.
